{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491193","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491193"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:37:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:37:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"864"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"864","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/864"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.39,0.22,0.22,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"864"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107849"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"864","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/864"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"864"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90269"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"559"},{"type":"tags","id":"1212"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"267"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15508"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38442"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107849","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107849"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with concerns about his right hand function. He reports injuring his right hand two months ago when he fell through a plate glass window. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. When asked to abduct both thumbs, the patient demonstrates reduced abduction of the right thumb compared to the left. Similarly the patient has reduced extension of the right thumb (Image). A healed laceration is visible on the dorsal aspect of his right wrist.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures is most likely to have been damaged?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Extensor pollicis brevis","Abductor pollicis longus","Extensor pollicis longus","Abductor pollicis brevis","Opponens pollicis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s right thumb cannot be fully extended or abducted compared to the left. This finding, along with the history of a laceration to the dorsal aspect of the wrist, suggests damage to the \u003Cstrong\u003Eabductor pollicis longus\u003C/strong\u003E. This muscle is one of the extrinsic muscles of the hand and, as its name implies, its primary role is to abduct and extend the thumb (give the \u0027thumbs up\u0027 sign) through its insertion into the base of the first metacarpal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExtensor pollicis brevis\u003C/strong\u003E works in conjunction with the abductor pollicis longus to extend and abduct the thumb. However, its primary role is to extend the thumb at the carpometacarpal joint. Isolated injury to this tendon would not typically result in such significant impairment of thumb abduction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExtensor pollicis longus\u003C/strong\u003E is responsible for the extension of the terminal phalanx of the thumb. Injury to this tendon would result in an inability to extend the interphalangeal joint of the thumb, which is not the primary finding in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbductor pollicis brevis\u003C/strong\u003E is an intrinsic muscle of the hand that helps move the thumb anteriorly and radially. It would not be affected by a laceration at the wrist level.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOpponens pollicis\u003C/strong\u003E facilitates opposition of the thumb, allowing the tip of the thumb to touch the tips of the other fingers. This movement is not being tested in the image, and the muscle would not be affected by a wrist laceration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe location of the healed laceration on the dorsal aspect of the wrist is consistent with the anatomical course of the abductor pollicis longus tendon. This further supports the diagnosis of abductor pollicis longus injury as the cause of the patient\u0027s impaired thumb abduction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The primary role of abductor pollicis longus is abduction of the thumb.","Abductor pollicis longus is an extrinsic muscle of the hand that inserts into the base of the first metacarpal.","Injury to the abductor pollicis longus results in impaired thumb abduction."],"references":["Gupta S, Michelsen-Jost H. Anatomy and Function of the Thenar Muscles.  Hand Clin 2012; 28:1-7. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22117918/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90269"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"864"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18408"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18408","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18408"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4951a7a3-6dbb-4aee-9a65-83ebfe62443d.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4951a7a3-6dbb-4aee-9a65-83ebfe62443d.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90269","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90269"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-03T09:13:03+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-03T09:14:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"864"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107849"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","i